A computer processes and stores information using its central processing unit (CPU) and memory. When the computer receives data, it converts it into binary code (0s and 1s) that can be understood by the CPU. The CPU then processes the data by performing mathematical and logical operations on it. The processed data is then stored in memory, which can be either volatile (RAM) or non-volatile (hard drive).
In contrast, living organisms process and store information using their nervous system and brain. The brain receives information from the senses and processes it using neurons and synapses. The processed information is then stored in the brain, which can be retrieved later for use.
